1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:03,375
What is clustering?

2
00:00:03,375 --> 00:00:05,430
A clustering algorithm looks at

3
00:00:05,430 --> 00:00:07,545
a number of data points and

4
00:00:07,545 --> 00:00:09,945
automatically finds
data points that are

5
00:00:09,945 --> 00:00:12,780
related or similar
to each other.

6
00:00:12,780 --> 00:00:14,940
Let's take a look
at what that means.

7
00:00:14,940 --> 00:00:17,070
Let me contrast clustering,

8
00:00:17,070 --> 00:00:19,910
which is an unsupervised
learning algorithm,

9
00:00:19,910 --> 00:00:22,475
with what you had
previously seen with

10
00:00:22,475 --> 00:00:25,585
supervised learning for
binary classification.

11
00:00:25,585 --> 00:00:32,670
Given a dataset like this
with features x_1 and x_2.

12
00:00:32,670 --> 00:00:36,665
With supervised learning, we
had a training set with both

13
00:00:36,665 --> 00:00:41,080
the input features x as
well as the labels y.

14
00:00:41,080 --> 00:00:44,750
We could plot a dataset
like this and fit, say,

15
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:46,790
a logistic regression
algorithm or

16
00:00:46,790 --> 00:00:50,635
a neural network to learn a
decision boundary like that.

17
00:00:50,635 --> 00:00:53,960
In supervised learning,
the dataset included

18
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:57,955
both the inputs x as well
as the target outputs y.

19
00:00:57,955 --> 00:01:01,280
In contrast, in
unsupervised learning,

20
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:05,060
you are given a dataset
like this with just x,

21
00:01:05,060 --> 00:01:08,770
but not the labels or
the target labels y.

22
00:01:08,770 --> 00:01:11,180
That's why when I
plot a dataset,

23
00:01:11,180 --> 00:01:12,890
it looks like this,

24
00:01:12,890 --> 00:01:15,410
with just dots rather
than two classes

25
00:01:15,410 --> 00:01:19,015
denoted by the x's and the o's.

26
00:01:19,015 --> 00:01:21,960
Because we don't have
target labels y,

27
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:23,690
we're not able to tell

28
00:01:23,690 --> 00:01:27,425
the algorithm what is
the "right answer,

29
00:01:27,425 --> 00:01:29,815
y" that we wanted to predict.

30
00:01:29,815 --> 00:01:32,600
Instead, we're going to
ask the algorithm to

31
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:35,080
find something interesting
about the data,

32
00:01:35,080 --> 00:01:36,860
that is to find some interesting

33
00:01:36,860 --> 00:01:38,950
structure about this data.

34
00:01:38,950 --> 00:01:42,320
But the first unsupervised
learning algorithm

35
00:01:42,320 --> 00:01:46,310
that you learn about is called
a clustering algorithm,

36
00:01:46,310 --> 00:01:48,440
which looks for one
particular type

37
00:01:48,440 --> 00:01:50,405
of structure in the data.

38
00:01:50,405 --> 00:01:53,510
Namely, look at the dataset
like this and try to

39
00:01:53,510 --> 00:01:57,920
see if it can be
grouped into clusters,

40
00:01:57,920 --> 00:02:01,540
meaning groups of points that
are similar to each other.

41
00:02:01,540 --> 00:02:04,025
A clustering algorithm,
in this case,

42
00:02:04,025 --> 00:02:06,065
might find that this dataset

43
00:02:06,065 --> 00:02:09,935
comprises of data from
two clusters shown here.

44
